  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I disclose Interest free perpetual loan given by a parent to subsidiary as per Indian GAAPs in the companies of both, parent and subsidary?",
  "response": "Under Indian GAAP (Generally Accepted Accounting Principles), the disclosure of an interest-free perpetual loan given by a parent to a subsidiary involves addressing the appropriate accounting classifications, treatments, and disclosures in both the parent's and the subsidiary's financial statements. Here\u2019s a general guide:\n\n### Parent Company's Financial Statements:\n\n#### Initial Recognition:\n- **Investment:** The parent company should classify the loan as an investment in the subsidiary.\n- **Measurement:** Initially, the loan should be recognized at fair value. Given that the loan is interest-free and perpetual, the fair value might be complex to determine and could involve discounting future cash flows if any are expected or considering the nature of the financing as quasi-equity.\n\n#### Subsequent Measurement:\n- **Investment in Subsidiary:** The investment should be measured at cost or as per the equity method of accounting if the parent entity presents consolidated financial statements.\n- **Impairment:** Assess the investment for impairment periodically to ensure that the carrying amount is recoverable.\n\n#### Disclosure:\n- **Nature of Investment:** Disclose the nature and terms of the investment, including that it is an interest-free, perpetual loan.\n- **Policy:** Describe the accounting policy for investments in subsidiaries.\n- **Amounts:** Disclose the carrying amount of the investment in the subsidiary.\n- **Related Party Disclosures:** As part of related party transactions, disclose details as required by the accounting standards and regulations (e.g., AS 18).\n\n### Subsidiary Company's Financial Statements:\n\n#### Initial Recognition:\n- **Equity Contribution:** The subsidiary should classify the loan as equity if it\u2019s perpetual and does not have any repayment terms that are enforceable.\n- **Measurement:** Recognize the equity contribution at its fair value on initial recognition. Since the loan is interest-free, it may be inferred as a capital contribution by the parent.\n\n#### Subsequent Measurement:\n- **Equity:** As an equity instrument, it would not need to be re-measured subsequently.\n- **Disclosure:** Provide detailed disclosures about the nature of the perpetual loan and its recognition as equity.\n\n#### Disclosure:\n- **Nature:** Describe the nature of the contribution received from the parent (i.e., interest-free perpetual loan).\n- **Amounts:** Disclose the amount recognized as equity.\n- **Related Party Disclosure:** Include all necessary details under related party transactions for transparency (AS 18 requirements).\n\n### Additional Considerations:\n\n- **Standards Compliance:** Ensure all applicable standards such as Accounting Standard (AS) 18 (Related Party Disclosures), AS 13 (Accounting for Investments), and AS 1 (Disclosure of Accounting Policies) are adhered to.\n- **Regulatory Compliance:** Compliance with the Companies Act, 2013, and any other relevant regulations is essential (especially provisions related to inter-corporate loans and investments).\n\n### Consolidated Financial Statements:\n- When preparing consolidated financial statements, eliminate any intragroup transactions and balances between the parent and subsidiary per AS 21 (Consolidated Financial Statements).\n\nIt is always advisable to consult with a professional accountant or financial advisor who specializes in Indian GAAP to ensure complete compliance with all applicable accounting standards and regulatory requirements.",
